metadata.name: Junina #155
metadata.description:
"Junina" is a tribute to the June popular festivities in Brazil, when the streets and house facades are decorated on many cities, mainly on the Northeast Region of the country. Small flags, paper balloons, and lamps are hung on public space creating a very special atmosphere and colorful landscapes. 

Plenty of forr√≥ (traditional music), bonfires, fireworks, typical food and drinks are part of these festivities that celebrate rural popular culture. The ‚ÄúFestas Juninas‚Äù (June festivities) have an important affective place in the imaginary of the Brazilian population. 

"Junina" continues the experimentations with code of my previous work "Monotipia". The challenge of creating graphic compositions with simple elements remains. Searching and trying to delve deeper into ways to play with the rhythm and subtleties of transparencies, colors, shapes and textures.

This project is also an homage to the painters who made the Brazilian June festivities as the theme of their works, especially Alfredo Volpi (1896-1988) and Alberto da Veiga Guignard (1896-1962), but also Anita Malfatti (1889-1964), Emiliano Di Cavalcanti (1897-1976), Heitor dos Prazeres (1898-1966), and many others.

---
Features:
-> 8 palettes (rarest = grayscale)
-> 9 compositions
-> Elements: 6 geometric shapes OR mixed element compositions
-> 5 canvas formats: 
-----> tall portrait (9:16)
-----> portrait (2:3)
-----> square (1:1)
-----> landscape (3:2)
-----> wide landscape (16:9) = rarest
-> Border colors: 
-----> soft
-----> dark
-----> deep gray
-----> soberest color from palette
-----> random color from palette (rarest)

* The names of the color palettes are words related to popular June festivals. The decision to use untranslated expressions was made because these words carry many poetic meanings in Portuguese. For example, "cinza" means "gray" but also "ash". A word that refers to both the color and to the residue that results from burning wood in bonfires.

---
To save the image as a png file, type:
[1] save at actual size 
[2] save with 2000px height
[3] save with 3000px height
[4] save with 4000px height
[5] save with 5000px height

Depending on the size option, the render time can be long.

---
Created with p5.js

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #108
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to ‚Äúlush, green‚Äù and Brut means ‚Äúdry, raw, or unrefined.‚Äù

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth‚Ä¶ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÃàm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (2376‚Ää√ó‚Ää3360)

URL params in live mode:

metadata.description:
Human feature detection theory proposes that the human nervous system sorts and
filters incoming stimuli to allow a human to make sense of visual information,
though it might be just random visual appearances.

This series takes inspiration from the psychological Rorschachtest introduced
by Swiss psychologist Hermann Rorschach. Each token features a generative system
which tries to achieve such a cognitive stimulus to elicit Pareidolia or
clustering illusions.

The underlying algorithm uses an autonomous agent to create initial paint
strokes. The resultant pattern is used to perform a reaction diffusion
simulation controlled by four different noise functions.

Javascript, WebGL, THREE.js
Guido Schmidt
fxhash.xyz 2021/12/17

metadata.name: chor√©graphie #149
metadata.description:
‚Ä¶ divided in two,
like the parent in sound and motion.
yet not exactly the same, I get ‚Ä¶


chor√©graphie explores the algorithmic characteristics of recursion in audiovisual form.

The algorithm performs a recursive split. At each split stage, space is divided into four different sized quadrants. Each split stage will eventually spawn an oscillator or a synthesizer representing the current properties of recursion in sound. The process is recursively repeated until a maximum recursion depth is reached or an early return condition is met.
Additionally, an initial motion funnction is randomly selected and propageted through the recursion, so that each recursive split stage with move depending on it‚Äôs split properties in combination with time.

Click into the piece to start the audio. Each piece can be seeded with a new initial configuration by pressing the ‚Äòs‚Äô key.

¬© 2022 ‚Äî Guido Schmidt

Created with:
p5, tone, @thi.ng/color, random

metadata.name: Vacuole #333
metadata.description:
Vacuole emerged from a cellular automaton sketch to which I come back from time to time to experiment with different rules and mechanisms.

To celebrate #fxhashturnsone, I wanted to look for alternative forms than the classical top-to-bottom/bottow-to-top scanline growing behaviour. Vocuole instead uses a grid of fields, where each field is initialized with different rules, growing directions and settings. The system combines two different variations: classical elementary cellular automata rules and a copy-pixel/plasma rule, which takes pixels from the neighborhood with a noise-controled offset like a stamp.

metadata.name: isometry II - watercolor #72
metadata.description:
This piece is a marriage of sorts. It begins with my "cityscape" interactive piece originally minted on Hic Et Nunc (here: https://teia.art/objkt/439560). This piece was used as the cover of The Tickle #30, and also received a static mint on Rarible. 

Several months later, I re-visited the land of isometrics and "fake 3D" for my "isometry" piece here on fx(hash), and which you can find here: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/13199

I always wanted to do a true determinative piece in the style of the original "cityscapes," and this weekend I finally sat down and "ported" it to modern fx(hash) output. Since this piece and "isometry" share a commonality, I named this piece "isometry II," and added the "watercolor" as that was the original name of the piece before I minted it on H3N. 

I hope you enjoy it!

metadata.name: Flowingcles #21
metadata.description:
"Flowingcles" is a generative art piece that showcases a mesmerizing collection of  circles and abstract shapes. This unique collection invites art enthusiasts to embark on an inspiring visual journey.

Some pieces feature abstract shapes accompanied by a noise effect, reflecting restlessness and energy, while others present a more serene atmosphere with minimalized noise effects. These two approaches offer collectors the freedom to choose the one that resonates with them the most.

The "Flowingcles" collection consists of a total of 128 original pieces. Each artwork has been generated with a unique combination, ensuring individuality and distinctiveness. By incorporating these pieces into their collections, art enthusiasts can adorn their homes, offices, or galleries with a sense of unparalleled art experience and authenticity.

"Flowingcles" stands as a prominent example of modern art, showcasing dynamism, aesthetics, and originality. This collection pushes the boundaries of art and takes viewers on a captivating visual journey. Therefore, me invite art lovers to explore the "Flowingcles" collection and become a part of this visual spectacle:)

metadata.name: Cube on Cube #80
metadata.description:
This token generates a plottable SVG file, a different arrangement of cubes.
The cubes are designed in 2D view, then placed next to each other or on top of each other in eight different directions. The goal is to challenge the audience's mind to discover the holes or protrusions produced by placing the cubes together.
To produce random parts made of cubes, those in the same direction are merged together, which is a turning point in this project.
Do you need a different output from your piece?  Then use controllers!

Controllers 
G - Change light direction
F - Add/remove frame
L - Add/remove base lines
D - Change base lines direction
R - Reset to default settings
P - Save as PNG
S - Export high resolution SVG

Note : When you have a piece with many shapes, controllers may run delayed. (Depending on your device).

Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Megarid #24
metadata.description:
<----
However, Megarid was not without its challenges. Dark forces from distant lands sought to disrupt the peaceful balance. Wicked sorcerers and their minions tried to unleash chaos upon the town, aiming to seize its magical energies. Mayor Eldrin, aided by a group of courageous heroes, known as the Guardians of Megarid, stood as the last line of defense against these threats.
The Guardians, a diverse group of individuals with unique skills and backgrounds, swore to protect the town they loved. They journeyed through treacherous valleys, scaled formidable mountains, and explored the depths of the sea, facing perilous trials and battling formidable foes. With each victory, they ensured that Megarid remained a sanctuary of magic and harmony.
In Megarid, the extraordinary became ordinary, and dreams transformed into reality. It was a place where the power of unity and the belief in the extraordinary could conquer any darkness that threatened to overshadow its radiant spirit. The tale of Megarid, with its valleys, mountains, and sea, was etched into the annals of fantasy as a testament to the enduring power of magic and the resilience of the human spirit.
